rincoin-seeder
==============

Rincoin-seeder is a crawler for the Rincoin network, which exposes a
list of reliable nodes via a built-in DNS server.

It is the Rincoin community fork of Pieter Wuille's `bitcoin-seeder`
(the upstream library/codebase name is preserved in copyright lines
and a few internal comments). It is wire-compatible with the original
protocol but ships with the Rincoin defaults and a few extras
described below.

Features:
* regularly revisits known nodes to check their availability
* bans nodes after enough failures, or bad behaviour
* accepts nodes down to v0.3.19 to request new IP addresses from,
  but only reports good post-v0.3.24 nodes.
* keeps statistics over (exponential) windows of 2 hours, 8 hours,
  1 day and 1 week, to base decisions on.
* very low memory (a few tens of megabytes) and cpu requirements.
* crawlers run in parallel (by default 24 threads simultaneously).
* serves multiple DNS zones from a single process / single UDP/53
  socket (e.g. `seed.rincoin.net`, `seed.rincoin.org`, `seed.rin.so`).
* announces protocol version 70018 + subver
  `/rincoin-community-seeder:2.0.0/`, so it survives the customized
  halving activation that disconnects peers below `MIN_CUSTOMIZED_HALVING_PEER_PROTO_VERSION`.
* exposes per-thread DNS counters (`nRequests`, `nAnswered`,
  `nRefusedNoZone`, `nRefusedBadFilter`, `nRefusedFormat`) and
  per-second stats output suitable for monitoring (Zabbix / Prometheus
  via a small text-exporter wrapper).

REQUIREMENTS
------------

$ sudo apt-get install build-essential libboost-all-dev libssl-dev

USAGE
-----

Assuming you want to run a dns seed on dnsseed.example.com, you will
need an authorative NS record in example.com's domain record, pointing
to for example vps.example.com:

$ dig -t NS dnsseed.example.com

;; ANSWER SECTION
dnsseed.example.com.   86400    IN      NS     vps.example.com.

On the system vps.example.com, you can now run dnsseed:

./dnsseed -h dnsseed.example.com -n vps.example.com -m admin.example.com

If you want the DNS server to report SOA records, please provide an
e-mail address (with the @ part replaced by .) using -m. Each `-h`
must be paired with one `-n` and one `-m`.

MULTI-ZONE OPERATION
--------------------

A single seeder process can be authoritative for several DNS zones at
once, sharing one privileged UDP/53 socket and one crawler database.
This is useful when you want to publish the same set of crawl results
under multiple seed FQDNs without running (and hardening, monitoring,
draining, ...) several daemons.

Repeat `-h`, `-n` and `-m` once per zone. The N-th `-h` is paired with
the N-th `-n` and the N-th `-m`, so the order matters:

  ./dnsseed \
      -h seed.rincoin.net -n ns.example.com -m admin.example.com \
      -h seed.rincoin.org -n ns.example.com -m admin.example.com \
      -h seed.rin.so      -n ns.example.com -m admin.example.com

For each configured zone, set up an `NS` record at the parent domain
pointing at the host where dnsseed is running. Verify with:

  $ dig @<seeder-ip> -p 53 NS  seed.rincoin.net
  $ dig @<seeder-ip> -p 53 SOA seed.rincoin.org
  $ dig @<seeder-ip> -p 53 A   seed.rin.so

Queries for any name *not* matching one of the configured zones are
answered with DNS RCODE 5 (REFUSED) and counted under the
`refusedZone` statistic so they are visible in the per-second log
line.

The well-known service-flag prefix form `xHHHH.<zone>` (e.g.
`x9.seed.rincoin.net` for `NODE_NETWORK | NODE_WITNESS`) works
identically across every configured zone. The set of accepted hex
masks is controlled by the built-in defaults and / or `-w`.

PROTOCOL VERSION & SUBVER
-------------------------

The seeder advertises `PROTOCOL_VERSION = 70018` (the Rincoin
`CUSTOMIZED_HALVING_VERSION`) and the subver string
`/rincoin-community-seeder:2.0.0/`. Both are defined at compile time
in `serialize.h` and `rincoin.cpp` respectively.

Why 70018:
  Rincoin Core's `net_processing.cpp` disconnects any peer announcing
  a `version < MIN_CUSTOMIZED_HALVING_PEER_PROTO_VERSION (= 70018)`
  once the customized halving has activated on the active chain. A
  seeder that still announced the legacy `60000` would be unable to
  finish version negotiation, would never receive `addr` messages,
  and the database would slowly rot until `IsGood()` rejects every
  entry. Bumping unconditionally is safe — pre-upgrade peers only
  enforce `nVersion >= MIN_PEER_PROTO_VERSION (= 31800)`.

If a future protocol bump happens, edit `PROTOCOL_VERSION` in
`serialize.h` and the subver string in `rincoin.cpp::PushVersion()`.

CUSTOMIZED HALVING ENFORCEMENT
------------------------------

Rincoin Core (`src/version.h`) defines
`MIN_CUSTOMIZED_HALVING_PEER_PROTO_VERSION = 70018`. Once the active
chain reaches `nCustomizedHalvingPhase4StartHeight` (mainnet 840000,
testnet 4200, regtest 600), Rincoin nodes refuse any peer that still
announces a protocol version below 70018. The seeder mirrors that
policy:

  1.  Every successful `TestNode()` updates a global high-water mark
      `nBestSeenHeight` with the peer's reported `nStartingHeight`.
  2.  `CAddrInfo::IsGood()` (db.h) treats a peer as not-good — and
      therefore never includes it in DNS answers — when
      `nBestSeenHeight >= nCustomizedHalvingHeight` AND the peer's
      `clientVersion < 70018`.
  3.  Such peers are *not* banned. They keep being crawled, so an
      operator who later upgrades is re-listed automatically on the
      next successful test cycle without having to wait out a ban
      window.

The activation height defaults to the per-network value above and
can be overridden with the `--customizedhalvingheight <N>` flag.
Pass `0` to disable the cutoff entirely (useful for private testnets
that never activate the upgrade). The current value is printed at
startup right after the network banner.

The cutoff only kicks in *after* the seeder has actually observed
the network crossing the activation height, so a freshly-started
seeder on a stale database does not immediately wipe its peer list
on the strength of an arbitrary configured number.

DEPLOYMENT NOTES
----------------

Two things bite operators every time:

1.  **Privileged port (UDP/53).** The seeder needs to bind a port
    < 1024. Either run as root, or grant the unit the right capability:

        [Service]
        AmbientCapabilities=CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE
        CapabilityBoundingSet=CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE

    Without this, every DNS thread fails its `bind()` and exits with
    `Permission denied`. The error is now logged loudly to stderr —
    check `journalctl -u <unit>` if the seeder appears to be running
    but `dig` times out / returns SERVFAIL.

2.  **Conflict with `systemd-resolved`.** On most modern distros
    `systemd-resolved` is bound to `127.0.0.53:53` and `127.0.0.54:53`.
    The seeder defaults to listening on the IPv6 wildcard `[::]:53`,
    which on Linux *overlaps* every local IPv4 address — including the
    `127.0.0.5x` stubs — and the kernel rejects the bind with
    `Address already in use`.

    The fix is to bind to your public IP explicitly:

        ExecStart=/var/rinseed/dnsseed -a <public-ip> ...

    Don't disable `systemd-resolved` unless you know what else on the
    box depends on it. If you also need IPv6 service, run a second
    seeder process with `-a <public-ipv6>`; the upstream code only
    supports a single `-a`.

3.  **In-bailiwick NS glue.** If you delegate `seed.example.net` to
    `ns1.seed.example.net`, the parent zone (`example.net`) must
    publish glue A/AAAA records for those names — otherwise resolvers
    can't bootstrap the lookup. The simpler alternative is to use
    *out-of-bailiwick* NS hostnames, e.g. `ns1-seed.example.net`,
    which only need plain A records in the parent zone.

MONITORING
----------

The seeder writes a single status line per second to stdout:

  [yy-mm-dd HH:MM:SS] G/A available (T tried in S s, N new, X active),
                      B banned;
                      DNS req=R ans=AN refusedZone=Z refusedFilter=F
                      refusedFormat=O db=Q

Fields:
  G   nGood            — entries currently considered "good" (advertised)
  A   nAvail           — total entries known and not banned
  T   nTracked         — entries tested in the last window
  S   nAge             — age of the oldest tracked entry, seconds
  N   nNew             — entries discovered but not yet tested
  X   nAvail-T-N       — entries currently being crawled
  B   nBanned          — banned entries
  R   nRequests        — total UDP DNS datagrams received
  AN  nAnswered        — replies that included at least one RR
  Z   nRefusedNoZone   — query name did not match any configured zone
  F   nRefusedBadFilter— `xHHHH.<zone>` mask was not in the whitelist
                          (returned NOERROR with empty answer section)
  O   nRefusedFormat   — malformed packet / bad opcode / multi-question
  Q   db               — internal cache misses against the address DB

The same counters are exposed via the in-memory `dns_opt_t` struct in
each DNS thread, so a Prometheus text-exporter or a Zabbix
UserParameter can scrape them by either:
  * tailing stdout (simplest), or
  * extending `ThreadStats` to also write a machine-readable line to a
    file / unix socket.

A separate `dnsstats.log` is appended once per dump cycle with the
aggregated reliability windows; see `dnsseed.dump` for the per-IP
breakdown (good flag, last success, uptime%, height, services, ver,
subver). All three files are simple text and easy to parse.

For external probing, any DNS resolver is enough:

  dig @<seeder-ip> -p 53 +short A    seed.rincoin.net | wc -l
  dig @<seeder-ip> -p 53 +short AAAA seed.rincoin.net | wc -l

A successful query that returns at least one address is the most
reliable single-shot liveness check.

COMPILING
---------

Compiling will require boost and ssl.  On debian systems, these are provided
by `libboost-dev` and `libssl-dev` respectively.

$ make

This will produce the `dnsseed` binary.

TESTING
-------

It's sometimes useful to test `dnsseed` locally to ensure it's giving good
output (either as part of development or sanity checking). You can inspect
`dnsseed.dump` to inspect all nodes being tracked for crawling, or you can
issue DNS requests directly. Example:

$ dig @:: -p 15353 dnsseed.example.com
       ^       ^    ^
       |       |    |__ Should match one of the -h hosts supplied to dnsseed
       |       |
       |       |_______ Port number (example uses the user space port; see below)
       |
       |_______________ Explicitly call the DNS server on localhost


RUNNING AS NON-ROOT
-------------------

Typically, you'll need root privileges to listen to port 53 (name service).

One solution is using an iptables rule (Linux only) to redirect it to
a non-privileged port:

$ iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p udp --dport 53 -j REDIRECT --to-port 15353

If properly configured, this will allow you to run dnsseed in userspace, using
the -p 15353 option.

Another solution is allowing a binary to bind to ports < 1024 with setcap (IPv6 access-safe)

$ setcap 'cap_net_bind_service=+ep' /path/to/dnsseed
